# React Migration Strategy

## Phase 1: Foundation (Weeks 1-2)

Set up tooling before touching components:

```bash
npm install --save-dev @typescript-eslint/parser @typescript-eslint/eslint-plugin
npm install --save-dev eslint-plugin-react-hooks
npm install --save-dev jest @testing-library/react @testing-library/user-event
```

Enable strict TypeScript:
```json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "strict": true,
    "noImplicitAny": true,
    "strictNullChecks": true
  }
}
```

## Phase 2: Prioritize Components

Migrate in this order:
1. **Leaf components** (no children) — lowest risk, highest ROI
2. **Shared UI components** (buttons, inputs, modals)
3. **Container components** with simple state
4. **Complex stateful components** last

Use this script to identify class components:
```bash
grep -r 'extends Component\|extends PureComponent' src/ --include='*.tsx' -l
```

## Phase 3: Class → Function Migration Pattern

```tsx
// BEFORE — Class component
class UserCard extends React.Component<Props, State> {
  state = { expanded: false };

  componentDidMount() {
    analytics.track('user_card_viewed', { userId: this.props.user.id });
  }

  componentDidUpdate(prevProps: Props) {
    if (prevProps.user.id !== this.props.user.id) {
      analytics.track('user_card_changed', { userId: this.props.user.id });
    }
  }

  render() {
    const { user } = this.props;
    const { expanded } = this.state;
    return (
      <div>
        <h2>{user.name}</h2>
        {expanded && <UserDetails user={user} />}
        <button onClick={() => this.setState({ expanded: !expanded })}>
          {expanded ? 'Collapse' : 'Expand'}
        </button>
      </div>
    );
  }
}

// AFTER — Functional component with hooks
const UserCard: React.FC<Props> = ({ user }) => {
  const [expanded, setExpanded] = useState(false);

  useEffect(() => {
    analytics.track('user_card_viewed', { userId: user.id });
  }, [user.id]);

  return (
    <div>
      <h2>{user.name}</h2>
      {expanded && <UserDetails user={user} />}
      <button onClick={() => setExpanded(prev => !prev)}>
        {expanded ? 'Collapse' : 'Expand'}
      </button>
    </div>
  );
};
```

## Phase 4: State Management Decision

| Concern | Redux | Zustand | Jotai | React Query |
|---------|-------|---------|-------|-------------|
| Server state | ❌ extra work | ❌ extra work | ❌ extra work | ✅ built-in |
| DevTools | ✅ excellent | ✅ good | ⚠️ basic | ✅ good |
| Boilerplate | ❌ high | ✅ minimal | ✅ minimal | ✅ minimal |
| Team familiarity | ✅ | ⚠️ | ⚠️ | ⚠️ |

**Recommendation**: Keep Redux for complex client state. Add React Query for all server/API state. This is additive — no big-bang rewrite.

## Phase 5: Accessibility Audit

```bash
npm install --save-dev axe-core @axe-core/react
npm install --save-dev eslint-plugin-jsx-a11y
```

Automate in CI:
```tsx
import { axe } from '@axe-core/react';

test('UserCard meets WCAG 2.1 AA', async () => {
  const { container } = render(<UserCard user={mockUser} />);
  const results = await axe(container);
  expect(results).toHaveNoViolations();
});
```

## Phase 6: Feature Flags

Use LaunchDarkly or a simple in-house solution:
```tsx
const UserCardV2 = lazy(() => import('./UserCard.v2'));

const UserCard = (props: Props) => {
  const { flags } = useFeatureFlags();
  if (flags.userCardV2) return <UserCardV2 {...props} />;
  return <UserCardLegacy {...props} />;
};
```

